[{"id":31161,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["one mole of ammonia","two moles of nitric acid","two moles of ammonia","one mole of nitric acid"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\mathrm{Mg}_3 \\mathrm{~N}_2+6 \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O} \\longrightarrow 3 \\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{OH})_2+2 \\mathrm{NH}_3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":31036,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The action of thionyl chloride with white phosphorus produces phosphorus trichloride,&nbsp;sulphur dioxide and sulphur monochloride.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn><msub><mi>SOCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>PCl<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;has a pyramidal shape,in which phosphorus is sp<sup> 3</sup> hybridised.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31022,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>ClONO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>HOCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>ClNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>ClONO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>HOCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>ClNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In the summer, nitrogen dioxide and methane react with chlorine monoxide and chlorine atoms which results in a shrinkage of chlorine and hence prevents ozone layer depletion.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cl</mi><mover><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow><mo>&#8729;</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#10230;</mo><mi>ClO</mi><munder><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></munder><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cl</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>During winter, special types of clouds are formed over the Antarctic region. These clouds provide the surface for the hydrolysis of chlorine nitrate to form hypochlorous&nbsp;acid.&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ClONO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>HOCl</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>So,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>ClONO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>HOCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31086,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Correct order of bond dissociation enthalpy of halogens is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>.</p><p>Due to inter electronic repulsions <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math> bond becomes weak and easily broken.</p><p>Bond dissociation energy of halogen family decreases down the group as the size of atom increases.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31003,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["Large size and high electronegativity","Small size and low electronegativity","Small size and high electronegativity","Large size and low electronegativity"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Due to its small size, Oxygen exhibits high electronegativity, a high charge/ radius ratio, and no d-orbital oxygen shows anomalous behaviour.</p><p>Oxygen exists as a diatomic molecule as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> comprising a double bond whereas all the other elements of group <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn></math> exist as polyatomic molecules.</p><p>Oxygen is paramagnetic and exists in a gaseous state at room temperature, which is completely opposite of the other Group <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn></math> elements.</p><p>The small size and high electronegativity of Oxygen enable it in the formation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pπ</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>pπ</mi></math> multiple bonds.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31056,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Se</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Te</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Se</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Te</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Te</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Se</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Se</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Te</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In general molar mass <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8593;</mo><mo>,</mo><mi>MP</mi><mo>&#8593;</mo></math> but in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> due to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>-bonding, it is maximum among the following:</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><strong>Property</strong></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Se</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Te</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">m</mi><mo mathvariant=\"bold\">.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">p</mi><mo mathvariant=\"bold\">.</mo><mo mathvariant=\"bold\">/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">K</mi></math></strong></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>273</mn></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>188</mn></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>208</mn></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>222</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30977,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["A and B only","B and C only","A, B, C and D","A, C and D Only"],"answer":2,"solution":"Statement A: The reducing nature of group 15 hydrides depends on the E-H bond strength. As the size of the central atom increases down the group, the E-H bond dissociation enthalpy decreases. Hence, the reducing character increases from NH$_3$ to BiH$_3$. This statement is correct.<br><br>Statement B: The basic character or the tendency to donate a lone pair of electrons depends on the electron density on the central atom. As the size of the central atom increases down the group, the electron density decreases. Thus, the basicity decreases from NH$_3$ to BiH$_3$. This statement is correct.<br><br>Statement C: Due to the decrease in E-H bond dissociation enthalpy down the group, the thermal stability of the hydrides decreases from NH$_3$ to BiH$_3$. This statement is correct.<br><br>Statement D: The H-E-H bond angle decreases down the group because the electronegativity of the central atom decreases and the size increases, causing the bond pairs to move further away from the central atom. This decreases the bond pair-bond pair repulsion. The bond angles are NH$_3$ ($107.8^{\\circ}$), PH$_3$ ($93.6^{\\circ}$), AsH$_3$ ($91.8^{\\circ}$), and SbH$_3$ ($91.3^{\\circ}$). This statement is correct.<br><br>All statements A, B, C, and D are correct.<br><br>Answer: A, B, C and D","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (08 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30998,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SbH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BiH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The reducing character of the hydrides of Group <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn></math> elements increases from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BiH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> (Bismuthine) because the reducing character depends upon the stability of the hydride.The greater the unstability of hydride,the greater is the its reducing character. Since,the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BiH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is the least stable (because the size of central atom is greatest &amp; therefore its tendency to form stable covalent bond with small hydrogen atom decreases,as a result the bond strength decreases) in this series,hence the reducing character increases.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31090,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>NO</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31142,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["Silicic acid","Calcium fluorosilicate","Hydrofluorosilicic acid","Silica gel"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Reactions involved are<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>CaF</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mfenced><mrow><mi>Conc</mi><mo>.</mo></mrow></mfenced></mtd><mtd><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi></mover></mtd><mtd><msub><mi>CaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>HF</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>HF</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced></mtd><mtd><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi></mover></mtd><mtd><msub><mi>SiF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>SiF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>&#8594;</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SiF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>The mixture after hydrolysis apperas as white gelatinous precipitate.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31067,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CdS</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>PbS</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>As</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CuS</mi><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;are soluble in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>%</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> while <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HgS</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Sb</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> are insoluble in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>%</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HgS</mi></math> soluble in aqua regia.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31007,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub></math>, each phosphorus undergo&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;hybridisation. It has one P-O-P linkage in it.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fb6c96c4-dc22-42ec-b689-7f060433e42b.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 155px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>HPO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0479229f-5531-4a56-baa7-09b2ed940eb7.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 236px;\" /></p><p>In&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>HPO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub></math>, each phosphorus undergo&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;hybridisation. It has three&nbsp;P-O-P linkages in it.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>10</mn></msub></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2ce69697-6301-48d2-a97f-177cbca5c605.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 212px;\" /></p><p>In&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>10</mn></msub></math>, each phosphorus undergo&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;hybridisation. It has six&nbsp;P-O-P linkages in it.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31015,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>To determine the ratio of sigma and pi bonds in pyrophosphoric acid, we first need to understand the molecular structure of the compound.</p><p>Pyrophosphoric acid has the chemical formula <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub></math>. The molecule contains two phosphorus atoms, seven oxygen atoms, and four hydrogen atoms.</p><p>The structure of pyrophosphoric acid is<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/66a8fc03-a21b-4df2-8463-af37876b3c6d-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 144px;\" /></p><p>It contains total&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn></math>&nbsp;sigma bonds and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;pi bonds. So<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mtext>&#160;No. of&#160;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#963;</mi><mtext>&#160;bonds&#160;</mtext></mrow><mrow><mtext>&#160;No. of&#160;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mtext>&#160;bonds&#160;</mtext></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>12</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31062,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NI</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The size of halogen increases from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>. The <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math>&nbsp;bond is stronger than other&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math>&nbsp;bonds due to the high electronegativity of fluorine. Larger the size of the halogen, less is the stability of nitrogen halide:</p><p>The stability order is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>NCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>NBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>NI</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30993,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["Dilute solution of sodium sulphate.","Acidified dilute solution of sodium sulphate.","Dilute solution of sulphuric acid","Concentrated solution of sulphuric acid"],"answer":3,"solution":"Theory based.\nAt anode :\n$2 \\mathrm{HSO}_4^{-} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S}_2 \\mathrm{O}_8+2 \\mathrm{e}^{-}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31163,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["oxygen in air reacts with the emitted HCI gas to form a cloud of chlorine gas","strong affinity of HCI gas for miosture in air results in forming of droplets of liquid solution which appears like a cloudy smoke.","due to strong affinity for water, concentrated hydrochloric acid pulls moisture of air towards it self. This moisture forms droplets of water and hence the cloud.","concentrated hydrochloric acid emits strongly smelling HCI gas all the time."],"answer":0,"solution":"$4 \\mathrm{HCI}+\\mathrm{O}_2 \\rightarrow 2 \\mathrm{Cl}_2+2 \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}$\n                    Cloud of white fumes","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":31097,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Phosphinic acid is hypo phosphorous acid&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>NaH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p>For neutrization</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mi>acid</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mi>base</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mi>mL</mi></msub></mfenced><mi>NaOH</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mi>NaOH</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31055,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>104</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>111</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>90</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>111</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Peroxodisulphate, obtained by electrolytic oxidation of acidified sulphate solutions at high current density, on hydrolysis yields hydrogen peroxide.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msubsup><mi>HSO</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Electrolysis</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>HO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>SOOSO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>Hydrolysis</mi></mover><mn>2</mn><msubsup><mi>HSO</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Hydrogen peroxide has a non-planar structure. The molecular dimensions in the gas phase and solid phase are shown</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4e65b6b3-b1dd-417e-bda7-3f3ffa7e9c4f-cc2a42f8-07c1-4b6e-84cc-3231bdbcac5d-9706269.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 246px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> structure in gas phase, dihedral angle is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>111</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> structure in solid phase at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>110</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math>, dihedral angle is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>90</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31059,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is a yellowish white powder and in moist air, it hydrolyses into&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>POCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and finally gets converted to phosphoric acid.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>POCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>HCl</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>POCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>HCl</mi></math></p><p>Phosphoric acid has 3 ionisable hydrogen atoms.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31118,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["5,3,0","$5,2,0$","4,2,2","4, 4, 0"],"answer":0,"solution":"Structure of $\\mathrm{XeO}_3 \\mathrm{~F}_2$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dnWawiXmHxPeWjyCKcEMAN_cI-Sg2OKrnhzfsRFQED4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":31071,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cc64331f-d795-4c02-9c60-9951f372557c-image.png\" style=\"width: 296px; height: 194px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31122,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>CO</mi><mn>3</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>","<math><msubsup><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>Na</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo></msubsup><mo>+</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msub><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><munder><mrow><mi>AgCl</mi><mo>&#8595;</mo></mrow><mi>White</mi></munder><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgCl</mi><mtext>&#8201;&#8201;</mtext><mo>+</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mi>dil</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>Does</mi><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>not</mi><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>dissolve</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":31009,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["It contains banana bonds","<p>It can react with water</p>","<p>It is a cyclic compound</p>","<p>It has electronic delocalization</p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The statement &quot;It contains a banana bond&quot; is incorrect about Borazine.</p><p>Borazine, also known as inorganic benzene or borazole, is a chemical compound with the formula <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math>. Borazine is a hexagonal planar molecule with alternating boron and nitrogen atoms, and it exhibits some structural and chemical similarities to benzene.&nbsp;Borazine is an aromatic compound with electron&nbsp;delocalization. It does not contain banana bond.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e48a0b6a-7428-4678-89fb-852a06f32df8-9928474.PNG\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 335px;\" /></p><p>On heating, borazine hydrolyses slowly.<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>9</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>BO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31096,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["tetrahedral <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msub><mi>PC</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>+</mo></msup></math> and octahedral <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>-</mo></msup></math>","square planar <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>+</mo></msup></math> and octahedral <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>-</mo></msup></math>","square pyramidal","trigonal bipyramidal"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><munder><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>+</mo></msup><mi>Tetrahedral</mi></munder><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><munder><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>-</mo></msup><mi>Octahedral</mi></munder></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31124,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["Five and four.","Four and five.","Five and five.","Four and four."],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ndryxumjjmsjqwephsharigkdauszsguwsetaucemimpvowmuw.jpeg\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 79px;\" /></p><p>As we can clearly see in the structure,</p><p>the number of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>OH</mi></math>&nbsp;bonds is 4.</p><p>The oxygen is an electronegative element and will always carry a negative charge. Now, it depends on its surrounding atoms about what charge it carries. In case of a hydroxyl group, the hydrogen carries a +1 charge. So, the opposite charge generated on the oxygen atom along with magnitude will be -1.<br />In the case of only oxygen atoms, we know that the oxidation number of oxygen is equal to -2. So, the charge generated on the adjacent atom of oxygen will be +2.<br />Thus, the oxidation state of phosphorus atom will be generated because of:<br />Oxidation state on phosphorous <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>[</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>]</mo></math>&nbsp;oxidation states<br /><br />Thus, the oxidation state of both the phosphorus atoms will be:<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31089,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi></math>-sulphur and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#946;</mi></math>-sulphur are diamagnetic. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>-form is paramagnetic.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30981,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":0,"solution":"Statement I is true. The oxidising power of halogens decreases down the group in the order $F_2 > Cl_2 > Br_2 > I_2$. A stronger oxidising halogen can displace a weaker oxidising halogen from its aqueous halide solution. This principle forms the basis of the layer test.<br><br>Statement II is true. In the layer test, chlorine water ($Cl_2$) is added to an aqueous solution containing bromide ($Br^-$) or iodide ($I^-$) ions. Since $Cl_2$ is a stronger oxidising agent, it oxidises $Br^-$ to $Br_2$ and $I^-$ to $I_2$. The reaction is given by:<br>$Cl_2 + 2X^- \\rightarrow 2Cl^- + X_2$ (where $X = Br, I$)<br>This is a non-metal displacement redox reaction. The liberated $Br_2$ or $I_2$ is then extracted into an organic solvent layer (like $CHCl_3$ or $CCl_4$), where it imparts a characteristic orange-red colour for $Br_2$ or a violet colour for $I_2$, thereby identifying them.<br><br>Therefore, both Statement I and Statement II are true.<br><br>Answer: Both Statement I and Statement II are true","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31005,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["Bromine","Iodine","Chlorine","Fluorine"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Because of the absence of d-orbitals, it is not possible for Fluorine to show variable oxidation state. Fluorine does not show variable oxidation states because it is the most electronegative element and has seven valence electrons. Its high electronegativity and strong attraction for electrons prevent it from losing electrons to exhibit different oxidation states. Fluorine always show <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math>oxidation state in compounds. Fluorine does not show variable oxidation state.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31103,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>.</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo>&#8594;</mo><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></mfenced></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo>+</mo><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></mfenced></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>AgCl</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>white</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ppt</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math> is <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></math> (bond order) <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1.67</mn></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31058,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ClONO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HOCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ClO</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Polar stratospheric clouds&nbsp;surface act on catalyst&nbsp;which provided surface on which hydrolysis of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ClONO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> takes place to form&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HOCl</mi></math> (Hypochlorous acid)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ClONO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>HOCl</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>Polar stratospheric clouds (PSCs) play a central role in the formation of&nbsp;the ozone hole&nbsp;in the Antarctic and Arctic.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null}]